<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:-7.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Item 7.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:-7.333px; text-indent:66px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Overview</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We are an insurance holding company engaged in the insurance and reinsurance business through our wholly owned insurance company, Independence American Insurance Company (&quot;Independence American&quot;), our marketing organizations, including our three medical stop-loss managing general underwriter subsidiaries (&#147;our MGUs&quot;), our two insurance and marketing agencies IPA and HIO, and our claims administration company, ECA. &nbsp;Since November 2002, AMIC has been affiliated with Independence Holding Company (&quot;IHC&quot;), which currently owns 49.7% of AMIC's stock, and IHC's senior management has provided direction to us through service agreements between us and IHC. &nbsp;In 2008, Independence American&#146;s primary source of revenue was reinsurance premiums. &nbsp;The majority of these premiums are ceded to Independence American from IHC under long-term reinsurance treaties to cede its gross medical stop-loss premiums 
written to Independence American. &nbsp;In addition, Independence American assumes fully insured health and short-term statutory disability benefit product in New York State (&quot;DBL&quot;) premiums from IHC, and assumes medical stop-loss premiums from unaffiliated carriers. &nbsp;Independence American began writing group major medical, medical stop-loss, major medical plans for individuals and families, and short-term medical in 2007. &nbsp;Given its A- (Excellent) rating from A.M. Best, Independence American expects to expand the distribution of its medical stop-loss products, and increase the business written on its paper, especially major medical plans for individuals and families.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While management considers a wide range of factors in its strategic planning, the overriding consideration is underwriting profitability. &nbsp;Management's assessment of trends in healthcare and in the medical stop-loss market play a significant role in determining whether to expand Independence American's health insurance premiums. &nbsp;Since Independence American reinsures a portion of all of the business produced by our MGUs, and since these companies are also eligible to earn profit sharing commissions based on the profitability of the business they place, our MGUs also emphasize underwriting profitability. &nbsp;In addition, management focuses on controlling operating costs. &nbsp;By sharing employees with IHC and sharing resources among our subsidiaries, we strive to maximize our earnings.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The following is a summary of key performance information and events:</P>

<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Net income per share decreased to $.11 per share, diluted, or $1.0 million, for the year ended December 31, 2008, compared to $.13 per share, diluted, or $1.1 million for the year ended December 31, 2007. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">17</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The book value of the Company decreased to $9.75 per share at December 31, 2008 compared to $9.96 per share at December 31, 2007, primarily due to the unrealized losses on the Company&#146;s investment portfolio.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Of the aggregate carrying value of the Company&#146;s investment assets, approximately 94.0% was invested in investment grade fixed maturities, securities purchased under resale agreements, and cash and cash equivalents at December 31, 2008. Also at such date, 99.6% of the Company's fixed maturities were investment grade.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The return on investments of the Company was 5.3% and 5.4% for the year ended December 31, 2008 and 2007, respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Premiums earned decreased 9% to $97.0 million for the year ended December 31, 2008 from $106.1 million for the year ended December 31, 2007, primarily due to a decrease in stop-loss and fully insured health premiums assumed from IHC, offset by an increase in direct fully insured health premiums and the additional premiums written by IPA (see Note 3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>For the year ended December 31, 2008, Independence American wrote $5.2 million of medical stop-loss business and $22.4 million of group major medical business pursuant to the Company&#146;s agreement with EDH.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>For the year ended December 31, 2008, Independence American wrote $4.3 million of individual health business produced by our marketing organization IPA, and ceded 50% to a third-party reinsurer.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Underwriting experience, as indicated by its GAAP Combined Ratios on our three lines of business for the year ended December 31, 2008 and 2007 are as follows:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:144px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Wingdings" align=justify>&#167;</P>

</TD><TD valign=bottom width=18><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=18><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="border-bottom:3px double #000000" valign=bottom width=72><P style="line-height:11pt; margin:0px; padding-left:-7.2px; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt" align=right>93.8%</P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="line-height:10pt; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-13.333px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=justify>(A)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Loss ratio represents insurance benefits claims and reserves divided by premiums earned.</P>
<P style="line-height:10pt; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-13.333px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=justify>(B)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Expense ratio represents net commissions (including profit commissions), administrative fees, premium taxes and other underwriting expenses divided by premiums earned.</P>
<P style="line-height:10pt; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-13.333px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt" align=justify>(C)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The combined ratio is equal to the sum of the loss ratio and the expense ratio.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In 2008, our MGUs and Agencies generated revenues of $15.0 million compared to $9.8 million in 2007, an increase of 53%, primarily due to income earned by HIO, IPA, and higher profit commissions, offset by lower fee income due to the lower volume of premium underwritten.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In 2008, our MGUs wrote an aggregate of $73.3 million of annualized gross premium compared to $87.2 million in 2007. &nbsp;This reduction in premiums was due, in part, to stricter underwriting guidelines and the continuing generally &quot;soft&quot; market. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company formed Excess Claims Administrators, Inc. (&#147;ECA&#148;) during 2008 to provide medical management services and adjudicate claims for our MGUs and independent managing general underwriters.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On April 1, 2008, the Company purchased the remaining 20% interest in Marlton, thereby increasing our interest in this medical stop-loss MGU to 100% (see Note 3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify>&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On April 15, 2008, the Company acquired a 51% interest in IPA (see Note 3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>CRITICAL ACCOUNTING POLICIES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The accounting and reporting policies of the Company conform to U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (&quot;GAAP&quot;). The preparation of the Consolidated Financial Statements in conformity with GAAP requires the Company's management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the amounts reported in the financial statements and accompanying notes. Actual results could differ from those estimates. A summary of the Company's significant accounting policies and practices is provided in Note 1 of the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8. Management has identified the accounting policies described below as those that, due to the judgments, estimates and assumptions inherent in those policies, are critical to an understanding of the Company's Consolidated Financial Statements and this Management's Discussion and Analysis.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Insurance Reserves</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, where material, including legal and other fees, for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. &nbsp;These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>maintained at levels that are estimated in accordance with GAAP. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s estimate of loss reserves represents management&#146;s best estimate of the Company&#146;s liability at the balance sheet date.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company&#146;s policies are short-duration and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period&#146;s claims or open claims from prior periods, including losses incurred for claims that have not been reported (&#147;IBNR&#148;). Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events. </P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management believes that the Company's methods of estimating the liabilities for insurance reserves provided appropriate levels of reserves at December 31, 2008. Changes in the Company's reserve estimates are recorded through a charge or credit to its earnings.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial"><B>Medical Stop-Loss</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company&#146;s medical stop-loss business is comprised of employer stop-loss and HMO Reinsurance. &nbsp;The two &#147;primary&#148; or &#147;key&#148; assumptions underlying the calculation of loss reserves for medical stop-loss business are (i) projected net loss ratio, and (ii) claim development patterns. &nbsp;The projected net loss ratio is set at expected levels consistent with the underlying assumptions (&#147;Projected Net Loss Ratio&#148;). Claim development patterns are set quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history (&#147;Claim Development Patterns&#148;). &nbsp;The Company uses the Projected Net Loss Ratio to establish reserves until developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results and it is feasible to set reserves based on Claim Development Patterns. &nbsp;The Company has concluded that a reasonably likely change in the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumpt
ion could have a material effect on the Company&#146;s financial condition, results of operations, or liquidity (&#147;Material Effect&#148;) but a reasonably likely change in the Claim Development Pattern would not have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Projected Net Loss Ratio</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Generally, during the first twelve months of an underwriting year, reserves for medical stop-loss are first set at the Projected Net Loss Ratio, which is determined using assumptions developed using completed prior experience trended forward. The Projected Net Loss Ratio is the Company&#146;s best estimate of future performance until such time as developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While the Company establishes a best estimate of the Projected Net Loss Ratio, actual experience may deviate from this estimate. &nbsp;This was the case with the 2005, 2006 and 2007 underwriting years that increased (decreased) by 8.0, 9.6, and (2.0) Net Loss Ratio points, respectively. &nbsp;While the Company believes that larger variations are possible, based on the Company&#146;s experience to date, it is reasonably likely that the actual experience will fall within a range up to five Net Loss Ratio points above or below the expected Projected Net Loss Ratio for 2008 at December 31, 2008. &nbsp;The impact of these reasonably likely changes at December 31, 2008, would be an increase in net reserves (in the case of a higher ratio) or a decrease in net reserves (in the case of a lower ratio) of up to approximately $1.2 million with a corresponding increase or decrease in the pre-tax expense for insurance benefits, claims and reserve
s in the 2008 Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Major factors that affect the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption in reserving for medical stop-loss relate to: (i) frequency and severity of claims; (ii) changes in medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, the impact of new medical technology and changes in medical treatment protocols; and (iii) the adherence by the MGUs that produce and administer this business to applicable underwriting guidelines. &nbsp;Changes in these underlying factors are what determine the reasonably likely changes in the Projected Net Loss Ratio as discussed above.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Claim Development Patterns</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Subsequent to the first twelve months of an underwriting year, the Company&#146;s developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate losses. At this point, claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. &nbsp;Development factors based on historical patterns are applied to paid and reported claims to estimate fully developed claims. Claim </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">20</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Development Patterns are reviewed quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history. The Company must determine whether changes in development represent true indications of emerging experience or are simply due to random claim fluctuations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company also establishes its best estimates of claim development factors to be applied to more developed treaty year experience. &nbsp;While these factors are based on historical Claim Development Patterns, actual claim development may vary from these estimates. &nbsp;The Company does not believe that reasonably likely changes in its actual claim development patterns would have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Predicting ultimate claims and estimating reserves in medical stop-loss is more complex than fully insured medical and disability business due to the &#147;excess of loss&#148; nature of these products with very high deductibles applying to specific claims on any individual claimant and in the aggregate for a given group.&nbsp; The level of these deductibles makes it more difficult to predict the amount and payment pattern of such claims. &nbsp;Fluctuations in results for specific coverage are primarily due to the severity and frequency of individual&nbsp;claims, whereas fluctuations in aggregate coverage are largely attributable to frequency of underlying claims rather than severity. Liabilities for first dollar medical reserves and disability coverages are computed using completion factors and expected loss ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Due to the short-term nature of medical stop-loss, redundancies or deficiencies will typically emerge during the course of the following year rather than over a number of years. &nbsp;For Employer Stop-Loss, as noted above, the Company maintains its reserves based on underlying assumptions until it determines that an adjustment is appropriate based on emerging experience from all of its MGUs for prior underwriting years. &nbsp;Reserves for HMO Reinsurance are adjusted on a policy by policy basis. &nbsp;Because of the small number of HMO Reinsurance policies it writes, the Company is able to evaluate each policy individually for potential liability by reviewing open claims with each HMO and applying completion factors using historical data.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Fully Insured Health</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Reserves for fully insured medical and dental business are established using historical claim development patterns. &nbsp;Claim development by number of months elapsed from the incurred month is studied each month and development factors are calculated. &nbsp;These claim development factors are then applied to the amount of claims paid to date for each incurred month to estimate fully complete claims. &nbsp;The difference between fully complete claims and the claims paid to date is the estimated reserve. &nbsp;Total reserves are the sum of the reserves for all incurred months.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The primary assumption in the determination of fully insured health reserves is that historical claim development patterns are representative of future claim development patterns. &nbsp;Factors which may affect this assumption include changes in claim payment processing times and procedures, changes in product design, changes in time delay in submission of claims and the incidence of unusually large claims. &nbsp;The reserving analysis includes a review of claim processing statistical measures and large claim early notifications; the potential impact of any changes in these factors are minimal. &nbsp;The time delay in submission of claims tends to be stable over time and not subject to significant volatility. &nbsp;Since our analysis considered a variety of outcomes related to these factors, the Company does not believe that any reasonably likely change in these factors will have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Premium and MGU Fee Income Revenue Recognition </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Direct and assumed premiums from short-duration contracts are recognized as revenue over the period of the contracts in proportion to the amount of insurance protection provided. &nbsp;The Company records MGU fee income as policy premium payments are earned. &nbsp;Our MGUs are compensated in two ways. &nbsp;They earn fee income based on the volume of business produced, and collect profit-sharing commissions if such business exceeds certain profitability benchmarks. &nbsp;Profit-sharing commissions are accounted for beginning in the period in which the Company believes they are reasonably estimable, which is typically at the point that claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">21</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B><I>Reinsurance</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Amounts recoverable or paid for under reinsurance contracts are included in total assets or total liabilities as due from reinsurers or due to reinsurers. &nbsp;In 2008, Independence American derived most of its business from pro rata quota share reinsurance treaties with Standard Security Life and Madison National Life, which are wholly owned subsidiaries of IHC. &nbsp;These treaties terminate on December 31, 2014, unless terminated sooner by Independence American. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life must cede at least 15% of their medical stop-loss business to Independence American under these treaties. &nbsp;Additionally, Standard Security Life, Madison National Life and Independence American have received regulatory approval to cede up to 30% to Independence American under most of IHC&#146;s medical stop-loss programs. For each of the twelve months ended December 31, 2008 and 2007, Standard Security Life and Madis
on National Life ceded an average of approximately 23% of their medical stop-loss business to Independence American. Independence American reinsures 20% of Standard Security Life&#146;s DBL business. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life also ceded approximately 8.9% of the majority of their fully insured health business to Independence American. &nbsp;In addition, in 2008, Independence American ceded 50% of its short-term medical (&#147;STM&#148;) and major medical for individuals and families business to unaffiliated reinsurers.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Taxes</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In assessing the realizability of deferred tax assets, management considers<B> </B>whether it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized. The ultimate realization of deferred tax assets is dependent upon the generation of future taxable income during the period in which those temporary differences become deductible. &nbsp;Management considers the scheduled reversal of deferred tax liabilities, projected future taxable income, and tax planning strategies in making this assessment. &nbsp;Management believes that although sufficient uncertainty exists regarding the future realization of deferred tax assets, the valuation allowance has been adjusted to account for the expected utilization of net operating losses against future taxable income.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has net operating loss carryforwards for federal income tax purposes available to reduce future income subject to income taxes. &nbsp;The net operating loss carryforwards expire between 2019 and 2028.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>U.S. Federal and California tax laws impose substantial restrictions on the utilization of net operating loss and credit carryforwards in the event of an &quot;ownership change&quot; for tax purposes, as defined in Section 382 of the Internal Revenue Code.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investments </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company accounts for its investments in debt and equity securities under SFAS No. 115 (&quot;SFAS 115&quot;), Accounting for Certain Investments in Debt and Equity Securities. &nbsp;The Company has classified all of its investments as available-for-sale or trading securities. &nbsp;These investments are carried at fair value with unrealized gains and losses reported in either accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) in the Consolidated Balance Sheets for available-for-sale securities or as unrealized gains or losses in the Consolidated Statements of Operations for trading securities. &nbsp;Fixed maturities and equity securities available-for-sale totaled $48.9 million and $49.4 million at December 31, 2008 and 2007, respectively. &nbsp;Premiums and discounts on debt securities purchased at other than par value are amortized and accreted, respectively, to interest income in the Consolidated Statements of Operations, using the co
nstant yield method over the period to maturity. &nbsp;Net realized gains and losses on investments are computed using the specific identification method and are reported in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company reviews its investment securities regularly and determines whether other than temporary impairments have occurred. &nbsp;If a decline in fair value is judged by management to be other than temporary, a loss is recognized by a charge to net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations, establishing a new cost basis for the security. &nbsp;The factors considered by management in its regular review include, but are not limited to: &nbsp;the length of time and extent to which the fair value has been less than cost; the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer; adverse changes in ratings announced by one or more rating agencies; whether the issuer of a debt security has remained current on principal and interest payments; </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">22</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>current expected cash flows; whether the decline in fair value appears to be issuer specific or, alternatively, a reflection of general market or industry conditions (including, in the case of fixed maturities, the effect of changes in market interest rates); and the Company's intent and ability to hold the security for a period of time sufficient to allow for a recovery in fair value. &nbsp;For the twelve months ended December 31, 2008, the Company recorded a loss of $1.0 million for other-than-temporary impairments from bonds and preferred stocks. &nbsp;<A NAME="OLE_LINK7"></A><A NAME="OLE_LINK8"></A></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2008, the Company had $1.9 million invested in whole loan CMOs backed by Alt-A mortgages. &nbsp;Of this amount, 46.3% were in CMOs that originated in 2005 or earlier and 53.7% were in CMOs that originated in 2006. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s mortgage security portfolio has no direct exposure to sub-prime mortgages. &nbsp;The unrealized loss for the equity securities was primarily due to wider spreads for preferred stocks issued by financial institutions following the disruption in credit markets in late 2007 and continuing in 2008. &nbsp;Some of these financial institutions have exposure to sub-prime mortgages. &nbsp;The unrealized loss for CMO securities is primarily attributable to Alt-A mortgages as described above. &nbsp;The unrealized losses on corporate securities are due to wider spreads. &nbsp;Spreads have widened as investors shifted funds to US Treasuries in response to the current market turmoil.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Goodwill and Other Intangibles</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite lives, which consist of licenses, are not amortized but are evaluated for impairment in the aggregate at the end of the fourth quarter of each year, or more frequently if indicators arise. &nbsp;If the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount (including goodwill), further evaluation is required to determine if a write-down of goodwill is required. &nbsp;Any impairment write-down of goodwill would be charged to expense. &nbsp;No impairment charge was required in 2008 or 2007. &nbsp;If the Company experiences a sustained decline in its results of operations and cash flows, or other indicators of impairment exist, the Company may incur a material non-cash charge to earnings relating to impairment of our goodwill, which could have a material adverse effect on our results.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:5.533px" align=justify><BR>

<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">23</P>

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Premiums Earned</U></I>. &nbsp;Premiums earned decreased 9%, or $9,116,000, to $96,984,000 for 2008, compared to $106,100,000 for 2007. &nbsp;The Company currently has three lines of business. &nbsp;Premiums relating to medical stop-loss business were $54,574,000 and $63,483,000 for 2008 and 2007, respectively. &nbsp;This change is primarily due to a decrease in medical stop-loss premiums assumed by Independence American ($9,239,000), partially offset by an increase in medical stop-loss written by Independence American ($330,000). &nbsp;Premiums relating to group major medical, STM and individual health were $38,975,000 and $39,136,000 for 2008 and 2007, </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">24</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>respectively. &nbsp;The increase is primarily due to an increase in premiums written by Independence American, offset by a net decrease in group major medical and STM premiums assumed from IHC. &nbsp;Premiums relating to DBL were $3,435,000 and $3,481,000 for 2008 and 2007, respectively, a decrease due to a reduction in rates. &nbsp;For 2008, Independence American assumed 10% of IHC&#146;s STM business, 8.8% of certain of IHC&#146;s group major medical business, 20% of IHC&#146;s DBL business and approximately 23% of IHC&#146;s medical stop-loss business. &nbsp;There were no significant changes to these percentages from the prior year.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>MGU and Agency Income</U></I>. &nbsp;MGU and agency income increased $5,087,000 to $14,539,000 for 2008, compared to $9,452,000 for 2007. &nbsp;MGU fee income-administration decreased $1,319,000 to $7,822,000 for 2008, compared to $9,141,000 for 2007, as our MGUs have decreased their volume of business as a result of stricter underwriting guidelines. &nbsp;MGU fee income-profit commission increased $779,000 to $1,036,000 for 2008, compared to $257,000 for 2007 as a result of more favorable loss ratios experienced at certain of our MGUs. &nbsp;Profit commissions for a given year are based primarily on the performance of business written during portions of the three preceding years. &nbsp;Therefore, profit commissions for 2008 are based on business written during portions of 2005, 2006 and 2007. &nbsp;In 2008, income from our Agencies consisted of commission income and other fees of $4,716,000 from IPA <A NAME="OLE_LINK11"></A><A NA
ME="OLE_LINK12"></A>and revenue of $965,000 from HIO. &nbsp;In 2007, income from our Agencies consisted of revenue of $54,000 from HIO. &nbsp;IPA was acquired subsequent to December 31, 2007 and ECA commenced operations in the fourth quarter of 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Investment Income</U>.</I> &nbsp;Net investment income decreased $84,000 to $3,527,000 for 2008, compared to $3,611,000 for 2007 due to lower average investible assets as a result of the Marlton and IPA acquisitions in the second quarter of 2008, and a lower return on investments. &nbsp;The return on investments of the Company was 5.3% and 5.4% for 2008 and 2007, respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Realized Investment Gains (Losses)</U>.</I> &nbsp;The Company recorded a net realized investment loss of $2,902,000 for 2008, compared to a gain of $321,000 for 2007. &nbsp;For 2008 and 2007, the Company recorded a loss of $1,006,000 and $0, respectively, for other-than-temporary impairments. &nbsp;The loss of $1,006,000 for 2008 represents a loss on bonds and preferred stock that the Company determined to be other-than-temporary due to the severity of the decrease in fair values and the length of time that these securities were in a loss position. &nbsp;In the fourth quarter of 2008, the Company became aware of certain activities engaged in by the non-affiliate broker-dealer that managed a trading account of the Company. &nbsp;Accordingly, the Company recorded a $2,006,000 loss, net of expected recoveries, in the fourth quarter of 2008 relating to assets invested with this broker-dealer. &nbsp;See Note 5 of Notes to Consolida
ted Financial Statements for additional information. &nbsp;The Company's decision as to whether to sell securities is based on management&#146;s ongoing evaluation of investment opportunities and economic market conditions, thus creating fluctuations in realized gains or losses from period to period. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Other Income (Loss)</U>.</I> &nbsp;Other income was $1,164,000 for 2008 compared to a loss of $388,000 for 2007. &nbsp;Included in 2008 is income of $1,043,000 representing a decrease in the fair value of the derivative liability relating to the agreement with Employers Direct Health, Inc. (&#147;EDH&#148;) (see Note 19 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements). &nbsp;Included in 2007 is a loss of $409,000 representing an increase in the fair value of the derivative liability relating to the agreement with EDH. &nbsp;The unrealized gain for 2008 reflects the probability of a lower future payment due to EDH as a result of less favorable loss ratios on this business.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Insurance Benefits, Claims and Reserves.</U></I> &nbsp;Insurance benefits claims and reserves decreased 11%, or $8,504,000, to $70,114,000 for 2008, compared to $78,618,000 for 2007. &nbsp;The decrease of $8,504,000 is primarily comprised of a $9,729,000 decrease in medical stop-loss due to a decrease in volume of business written and improved loss ratios (the Company recorded $4,500,000 of reserve strengthening in the prior year), partially offset by a $1,540,000 increase in fully insured health as a result of higher claims and an overestimation of a PPO discount on business from the group major medical program, and higher losses on group major medical business assumed from IHC.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Selling, General and Administrative</U></I>. &nbsp;Selling, general and administrative expenses increased $2,800,000 to<I> </I>$40,263,000 for 2008, compared to $37,463,000 for 2007. &nbsp;This increase is primarily due to the additional expense of IPA of $5,540,000, which includes commissions and other general expenses of the agency, and higher underwriting expenses inclusive of administration fees of $702,000, offset by lower commissions expense </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">25</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>of $3,134,000 incurred by Independence American primarily resulting from a decrease in premiums assumed in medical stop-loss business.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Amortization and Depreciation</U>.</I> &nbsp;Amortization and depreciation expense decreased $178,000 to $793,000 for 2008, compared to $971,000 for 2007. &nbsp;The decrease in amortization is the result of the Company fully amortizing the intangible asset associated with previous broker/TPA relationships in the prior year, offset by additional amortization expense as a result of the acquisition of the remaining 20% interest in Marlton and the acquisition of 51% of IPA (see Note 4 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Minority Interest</U></I>. &nbsp;&nbsp;The Company recorded minority interest expense of $471,000 for 2008 and $215,000 for 2007. &nbsp;The 2008 expense relates to the 49% minority interest in IPA, the 49% minority interest in HIO, and the 20% minority interest in Marlton for the first quarter ended March 31, 2008. &nbsp;The 2007 expense relates to the 20% minority interest in Marlton.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Income Taxes.</U> &nbsp;<A NAME="OLE_LINK28"></A><A NAME="OLE_LINK29"></A></I>The provision for income taxes decreased $60,000 to $631,000, an effective rate of 37.8%, for 2008, compared to $691,000, an effective rate of 37.8%, for 2007. &nbsp;Net income for 2008 and 2007 includes a non-cash provision for federal income taxes of $497,000 and $518,000, respectively. &nbsp;The state tax effective rate decreased to 8.1% for 2008 from 8.4% for 2007. &nbsp;As compared to our MGUs, Independence American pays a nominal amount of state income tax; therefore, the Company&#146;s state tax effective rate will increase relative to a decrease in Independence American&#146;s pre-tax income. &nbsp;For as long as AMIC utilizes its NOL carryforwards, it will not pay any income taxes, except for federal alternative minimum taxes and state income taxes.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Gain (loss) on Discontinued Operations.</U></I> &nbsp;Loss on discontinued operations, net of tax was $75,000 for 2008, compared to $0 for 2007. &nbsp;The loss of $75,000 was due to the loss of rental income associated with the sublease of a property located in Livermore, California, and a re-estimation of expected expenses related to the lease (see Note 9 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Income</U>.</I> &nbsp;The Company&#146;s net income decreased 15% to $965,000, or $.11 per share, diluted, for 2008, compared to $1,138,000, or $.13 per share, diluted, for 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Independence American</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American principally derives cash flow from: (i) operations; (ii) the receipt of scheduled principal payments on its portfolio of fixed income securities; and (iii) earnings on investments and other investing activities. &nbsp;Such cash flow is partially used to finance liabilities for insurance policy benefits and reinsurance obligations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Corporate</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Corporate derives cash flow funds principally from dividends and tax payments from its subsidiaries and investment income from corporate liquidity. &nbsp;Other than Independence American, there are no regulatory constraints on the ability of any of our subsidiaries to pay dividends to its parent company. &nbsp;Delaware insurance laws and regulations govern the ability of Independence American to pay dividends to its parent company. &nbsp;For the twelve months ended December 31, 2008, our MGUs and agencies paid $3,025,000 in dividends to Corporate.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Cash Flows</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As of December 31, 2008, the Company had $57,248,000 of cash, cash equivalents, and investments net of amounts due to/from brokers compared with $66,432,000 as of December 31, 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">26</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Net cash provided by operating activities of continuing operations for the year ended December 31, 2008 was $2,603,000. &nbsp;Net cash flows were the result of insurance revenues and fees from our MGUs, partially offset by claims and losses.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Net cash used by investing activities of continuing operations for the year ended December 31, 2008 was $4,338,000. &nbsp;This resulted from purchases of ownership interests in IPA and Marlton (see Note 3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2008, the Company had $6,980,000 of restricted cash at our MGUs. &nbsp;The amount at our MGUs is directly offset by corresponding liabilities for Premium and Claim Funds Payable of $6,980,000. This asset, in part, represents the premium that is remitted by the insureds and is collected by our MGUs on behalf of the insurance carriers they represent. &nbsp;Each month the premium is remitted to the insurance carriers by our MGUs. &nbsp;Until such remittance is made the collected premium is carried as an asset on the balance sheet of each of our MGUs with a corresponding payable to each insurance carrier. &nbsp;In addition to the premium being held at our MGUs, our MGUs are in possession of cash to pay claims. &nbsp;The cash is deposited by each insurance carrier into a bank account that our MGUs can access. &nbsp;The cash is used by our MGUs to pay claims on behalf of the insurance carriers they represent. &nbsp;The availab
ility of cash enables our MGUs to reimburse claims in a timely manner.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2008, the Company had $32,760,000 of insurance reserves that it expects to pay out of current assets and cash flows from future business. &nbsp;If necessary, the Company could utilize the cash received from maturities and repayments of its fixed maturity investments if the timing of claim payments associated with the Company's insurance resources does not coincide with future cash flows.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company believes it has sufficient cash to meet its currently anticipated business requirements over the next twelve months including the funding of discontinued operations, working capital requirements, and capital investments. The Company expects continued cash usage similar to the amount used in 2008 for its discontinued operations, which are primarily lease obligations, for the year ending December 31, 2009.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Asset Quality and Investment Impairments</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The nature and quality of insurance company investments must comply with all applicable insurance statutes and regulations which have been promulgated primarily for the protection of policyholders. &nbsp;Of the aggregate carrying value of the Company's investment assets, approximately 94.0% was invested in investment grade fixed income securities, securities purchased under resale agreements, and cash and cash equivalents at December 31, 2008. &nbsp;The Company's gross unrealized losses on available-for-sale securities totaled $4,620,000 and $1,459,000 at December 31, 2008 and 2007, respectively. &nbsp;Substantially all of these securities were investment grade. &nbsp;The Company holds all fixed maturities and preferred stock as available-for-sale and accordingly marks all of its securities to market through accumulated other comprehensive income (loss). &nbsp;The Company does not have any non-performing fixed maturities at December 31,
 2008. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2008, the Company had $1.9 million invested in whole loan collateralized mortgage obligations (&#147;CMOs&#148;) backed by Alt-A mortgages. &nbsp;Of this amount, 46.3% were in CMOs that originated in 2005 or earlier and 53.7% were in CMOs that originated in 2006. &nbsp;While these mortgages have seen lower market values recently, we believe that the unrealized losses on these securities are not necessarily indicative of their ultimate performance. &nbsp;The Company's mortgage security portfolio has no direct exposure to sub-prime mortgages. &nbsp;The decline in fair value for the equity securities was primarily due to wider spreads for preferred stocks issued by financial institutions following the disruption in credit markets in late 2007. &nbsp;Some of these financial institutions have exposure to sub-prime mortgages. &nbsp;The unrealized loss for CMO securities is primarily attributable to Alt-A mortgages as described
 above. &nbsp;The unrealized losses on corporate securities are due to wider spreads. &nbsp;Spreads have widened as investors shifted funds to US Treasuries in response to the current market turmoil. &nbsp;Further deterioration in credit quality of the companies backing the securities, further deterioration in the condition of the financial services industry, a continuation of the current imbalances in liquidity that exist in the marketplace, a continuation or worsening of the current economic recession, or additional declines in real estate values may further affect the fair value of these securities and increase the </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">27</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>potential that certain unrealized losses be designated as other-than-temporary in future periods and the Company may incur additional write-downs.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<TR><TD valign=top width=114 colspan=2><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=18><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=72><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=18><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=90><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=18><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=108><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=18><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=90><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=18><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=66><P>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has chosen to carry its fixed maturity securities as available-for-sale. The unrealized losses on all available-for-sale securities have been evaluated in accordance with the Company's impairment policy (as disclosed in Note 2 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements) and were determined to be temporary in nature at December 31, 2008. &nbsp;In 2008, the Company experienced an increase in unrealized losses of $2,853,000 million which decreased stockholders' equity by $2,853,000 million (reflecting unrealized losses of $4,057,000 million at December 31, 2008 compared to unrealized losses of $1,204,000 million at December 31, 2007). &nbsp;From time to time, as warranted, the Company may employ investment strategies to mitigate interest rate and other market exposures.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>Balance Sheet</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Total investments decreased $7,301,000 to $52,847,000 at December 31, 2008 from $60,148,000 at December 31, 2007, due to unrealized losses and impairments of fixed income securities, the acquisitions of Marlton ($3,700,000) and IPA ($1,750,000), and the trading account loss of $2,006,000, net of expected recoveries, taken in the fourth quarter of 2008 relating to certain activities engaged in by the non-affiliate broker-dealer that managed a trading account of the Company. &nbsp;The $1,745,000 decrease in total stockholders' equity is primarily due to an increase of $2,853,000 in unrealized losses, offset by net income of $965,000 generated during 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company had receivables from reinsurers of $9,386,000 at December 31, 2008. &nbsp;Substantially all of the business ceded to such reinsurers is of short duration. &nbsp;All of such receivables are either due from related </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">28</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>parties, highly rated companies or are adequately secured. &nbsp;No allowance for doubtful accounts was deemed necessary at December 31, 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>CAPITAL RESOURCES</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As Independence American&#146;s total adjusted capital was significantly in excess of the authorized control level risk-based capital, the Company remains well positioned to increase or diversify its current activities. It is anticipated that future acquisitions or other expansion of operations will be funded internally from existing capital and surplus and parent company liquidity. In the event additional funds are required, it is expected that they would be borrowed or raised in the public or private capital markets to the extent determined to be necessary or desirable.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>OUTLOOK</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Independence American</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American, which is domiciled in Delaware, is licensed to write property and/or casualty insurance in 49 states and the District of Columbia, and has an A- (Excellent) rating from A.M. Best Company, Inc. (&quot;A.M. Best&quot;). An A.M. Best rating is assigned after an extensive quantitative and qualitative evaluation of a company's financial condition and operating performance, and is also based upon factors relevant to policyholders, agents, and intermediaries, and is not directed towards protection of investors. A.M. Best ratings are not recommendations to buy, sell or hold securities of the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Since its acquisition by AMIC in 2002, Independence American&#146;s primary source of revenue has been reinsurance premiums. &nbsp;During 2008, we began to become less dependent on reinsurance premiums as we increased the amount of business written by Independence American. &nbsp;During 2008, Independence American wrote group major medical, medical stop-loss, major medical plans for individuals and families, and a small amount of short-term medical. Given its A- (Excellent) rating from A.M. Best, Independence American expects to expand the distribution of its products. &nbsp;In late 2008, Independence American appointed a second MGU, which is expected to meaningfully increase the amount of medical stop-loss business written by Independence American in 2009, and we continue to seek additional production sources. &nbsp;With respect to major medical plans for individuals and families, the acquisition of a controlling interest in IPA, shoul
d meaningfully increase the amount of this line of business written by Independence American in 2009.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>IHC Treaties</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>With respect to the IHC Treaties, the Company&#146;s operating results are affected by the following factors: (i) the percentage of business ceded to Independence American pursuant to the IHC Treaties; (ii) the amount of gross premium written by Standard Security Life or Madison National Life that is ceded to the IHC Treaties; and (iii) the amount of gross premium produced by the MGUs and other distribution sources written by carriers other than Standard Security Life or Madison National Life that is ceded to Independence American. &nbsp;The profitability of the business ceded will also impact our operating results. &nbsp;Independence American assumes medical stop-loss, fully insured health and DBL premiums from IHC under the IHC Treaties.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Percentage of Business Ceded</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In 2009 and beyond, the percentage of medical stop-loss ceded to Independence American will depend on how much IHC determines it has available to reinsure and Independence American&#146;s desire to reinsure IHC&#146;s business. &nbsp;Since the percentage being ceded is now well in excess of the contractual minimum, there is no guaranty that IHC will continue to increase the percentage of business ceded to Independence American or, in fact, cede in excess of 15%. &nbsp;However, our MGUs are the largest producers of medical stop-loss business for IHC, controlling a majority of this premium in 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American reinsures 20% of Standard Security Life&#146;s DBL product. &nbsp;Standard Security Life is not contractually obligated to continue to cede this business to Independence American after termination of the current treaty year. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life ceded approximately 8.9% of the majority of their fully insured health business to Independence American. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">29</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Life are not contractually obligated to continue to cede this business to Independence American after termination of the current treaty years. &nbsp;The Company does not expect the percentage ceded to it from IHC will change significantly in the next twelve months.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>If Independence American, Standard Security Life, and Madison National Life had agreed to increase the average percentage ceded to Independence American by 1% (from the approximately 23% ceded for the twelve months ended December 31, 2008) and Standard Security Life&#146;s and Madison National Life&#146;s gross written premium had remained unchanged, Independence American&#146;s premium would have increased by approximately $1.8 million, which is approximately 1.8% of total net premiums earned for the year ended December 31, 2008. &nbsp;That increase in premium, however, would not have flowed directly to pre-tax operating income because of corresponding changes in insurance benefits, claims and reserves and other expenses attributable to the increase in premiums.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Amount of Premiums Written</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The gross medical stop-loss premiums written by IHC decreased in 2008 by 9.3% and such premiums produced by our MGUs decreased by 10.4% in 2008 as a result of writing and/or renewing fewer policies due to competitors' willingness to write business at profit margins lower than those acceptable to the Company, partially offset by increased rates on the policies retained. &nbsp;This resulted in a decrease in the gross amount of premium available to be ceded to Independence American in 2008, which decrease could extend into 2009. &nbsp;Our MGUs do not anticipate materially increasing their production of medical stop-loss business in 2009. &nbsp;IHC has reported that it expects its DBL and fully insured premiums to remain steady in 2009 </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Profitability</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The medical stop-loss market is generally cyclical in nature. When a product experiences several consecutive years of underwriting profitability, it is not unusual for there to be more competitors entering that line which can increase pressure on pricing and create a &#147;softer&#148; market. The medical stop-loss market began to &#147;soften&#148; in 2003 and less favorable conditions continued through 2008. &nbsp;As a result of these market conditions, the rate that the carriers that cede business to the Company were able to charge for medical stop-loss increased at a lesser rate in recent years although increases in medical trend have also been held in check to a greater extent and deductibles and attachment points have increased. This reduces the risk taker&#146;s overall risk exposure. &nbsp;Fully insured health business tends to be less volatile and less cyclical than excess insurance.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>Marketing Agreements</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In February 2006, Independence American entered into an agreement with a marketing organization with a block of fully insured health business, including CDHPs, primarily sold to small employer groups, and medical stop-loss, to begin writing for Independence American. &nbsp;The organization that produces this business began writing employer medical stop-loss through Independence American in 2006, and moved the majority of its existing block of fully insured and stop-loss health insurance to Independence American during 2007. &nbsp;Independence American will be the exclusive issuing carrier for business underwritten by this organization through December 31, 2011. &nbsp;Subject to certain conditions, the agreement will automatically extend until December 31, 2016, and this organization could be entitled to additional cash consideration (see Note 19 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In addition, in 2007 the Company entered into an agreement with IPA, a national career agent marketing organization, to begin marketing health plans to individuals and families utilizing Independence American as the carrier. &nbsp;Independence American retains 50% of the risk on this business. &nbsp;Gross premiums of $4,295,000 and $231,000 were written under this program in 2008 and 2007, respectively. &nbsp;The program is administered by Insurers Administrative Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of IHC. &nbsp;AMIC purchased a 51% interest in IPA in April 2008 (see Note 3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">31</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center>&nbsp;<B><U>Report of Management on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The management of American Independence Corp. (&quot;AMIC&quot;) is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting. AMIC's internal control system was designed to provide reasonable assurance to the Company's management and Board of Directors regarding reliability of financial reporting and the preparation and fair presentation of published financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All internal control systems, no matter how well designed, have inherent limitations. Therefore, even those systems determined to be effective can provide only reasonable assurance with respect to financial statement preparation and presentation. &nbsp;Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management assessed the effectiveness of AMIC's internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2008. In making this assessment, management used the criteria set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) in <I>Internal Control &#150;Integrated Framework</I>. Based on our assessment we concluded that, as of December 31, 2008, AMIC's internal control over financial reporting is effective.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">32</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:14.467px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>&nbsp;Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.:</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries (the &#147;Company&#148;) as of December 31, 2008 and 2007, and the related consolidated statements of operations, stockholders&#146; equity and cash flows for the years then ended. In connection with our audits of the consolidated financial statements, we have also audited the financial statement schedules listed in the accompanying index. &nbsp;These consolidated financial statements are the responsibility of the Company&#146;s management. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these consolidated financial statements based on our audits.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We conducted our audits in accordance with the auditing standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. The Company is not required to have, nor were we engaged to perform, an audit of its internal control over financial reporting. &nbsp;Our audit included consideration of internal control over financial reporting as a basis for designing audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting. Accordingly, we express no such opinion. An audit also includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements, assessing the accounting p
rinciples used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of the Company as of December 31, 2008 and 2007, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for the years then ended in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;Also in our opinion, the related financial statement schedules, when considered in relation to the basic consolidated financial statements taken as a whole, present fairly, in all material respects, the information set forth therein.</P>
