<P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">37</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B>American Independence Corp. and Subsidiaries</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:24px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><B>1.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial"><B>Nature of Business</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>American Independence Corp. is a Delaware corporation (NASDAQ: AMIC). &nbsp;We are a holding company principally engaged in the insurance and reinsurance business through: a) our wholly owned insurance company, Independence American Insurance Company (&quot;Independence American&quot;); b) our managing general underwriter subsidiaries: IndependenceCare Holdings L.L.C. and its subsidiaries (collectively referred to as &quot;IndependenceCare&quot;); Risk Assessment Strategies, Inc. (&quot;RAS&quot;), and Marlton Risk Group LLC (&quot;Marlton&quot;); c) our 23% investment in Majestic Underwriters LLC (&quot;Majestic&quot;); d) our 51% ownership in HealthInsurance.org, LLC (&#147;HIO&#148;), an insurance and marketing agency; e) our 51% ownership in Independent Producers of America, LLC (&#147;IPA&#148;), a national career agent marketing organization; and f) our wholly owned claims administration company, Excess Claims Administrators, Inc.
 (&#147;ECA&#148;). &nbsp;IndependenceCare, RAS and Marlton are collectively referred to as &quot;our MGUs&quot;. &nbsp;HIO and IPA are collectively referred to as &#147;our Agencies&#148;.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Prior to November 14, 2002, the Company (then known as SoftNet Systems, Inc.) was a holding company principally engaged in providing Internet services. &nbsp;All previously reported business segments have ceased operations or have been sold, and accordingly are reported as discontinued operations (see Note 9 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Since November 2002, AMIC has been affiliated with Independence Holding Company (&quot;IHC&quot;), an insurance holding company, which held 49.7% of AMIC&#146;s outstanding common stock at December 31, 2008. &nbsp;The senior management of IHC provides direction to the Company through a service agreement between the Company and IHC. &nbsp;IHC has also entered into long-term reinsurance treaties through its wholly owned subsidiaries, Standard Security Life Insurance Company of New York (&#147;Standard Security Life&#148;) and Madison National Life Insurance Company, Inc. (&#147;Madison National Life&#148;), whereby the Company assumes reinsurance premiums from the following lines of business: medical stop-loss, New York statutory disability (&#147;DBL&#148;), short-term medical (&#147;STM&#148;) and group major medical.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:24px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><B>2.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial"><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Principles of Consolidation and Presentation of Financial Statements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The consolidated financial statements have been prepared in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (&#147;GAAP&#148;) and include the accounts of AMIC and its consolidated subsidiaries. All intercompany transactions have been eliminated in consolidation. The preparation of financial statements in conformity with U.S. GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect: &nbsp;(i) the reported amounts of assets and liabilities; (ii) the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements; and (iii) the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Immaterial Correction of an Error</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Minority interest is to be reported at the percentage of the historical financial statement carrying amounts of the net assets of the acquired enterprise based on the ownership interest of the remaining minority interest owners in the acquired enterprise. &nbsp;The Company incorrectly recorded minority interest from the January 1, 2003 acquisition of Marlton based on the fair value of the net assets of the acquired enterprise. &nbsp;Accordingly, the December 31, 2007 minority interest amount reflected on the consolidated balance sheet has been reduced by $3,987,000 with an </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">38</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>offsetting reduction to goodwill. &nbsp;This correction had no effect on consolidated stockholders' equity or on the results of operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Reclassifications</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Certain amounts in prior years' Consolidated Financial Statements and Notes thereto have been reclassified to conform to the 2008 presentation, primarily relating to the EDH Derivative (see Note 19 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investment in</I></B><I> </I><B><I>Majestic Underwriters LLC</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:61.067px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company's investment in Majestic Underwriters LLC (see Note 7 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements) is carried on the equity method with the Company's share of income or loss credited or charged, as appropriate, to net investment income in the Consolidated Statements of Operations with a corresponding charge to the Company's investment account. The Company also reduces its investment for its proportionate share of the amortization expense for the intangible assets recorded in the acquisition.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Goodwill and Other Intangibles</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite lives, which consist of licenses, are not amortized but are evaluated for impairment in the aggregate at the end of the third quarter of each year, or more frequently if indicators arise. &nbsp;If the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount (including goodwill), further evaluation is required to determine if a write-down of goodwill is required. &nbsp;Any impairment write-down of goodwill would be charged to expense. &nbsp;No impairment charge was required in 2008 or 2007.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2008, the Company&#146;s market capitalization was less than its book value indicating a potential impairment of goodwill. &nbsp;As a result, the Company assessed the factors contributing to the performance of AMIC stock in 2008. &nbsp;As a result of this assessment, the Company does not believe that an impairment of goodwill exists at this time (see Note 3 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company's intangible assets with definite lives, consisting of broker/third party relationships and marketing agreements, are amortized over the expected life of the assets (see Note 4 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Fair Value of Financial Instruments</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The carrying amount of cash and cash equivalents, restricted cash, short-term investments, due from reinsurers and premiums receivable approximates their fair values.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Cash, Cash Equivalents and Restricted Cash</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Cash and cash equivalents consist of cash and highly liquid securities with maturities of three months or less from date of purchase. &nbsp;Restricted cash primarily consists of funds held by our MGUs for the benefit of their insurers and reinsurers. &nbsp;These funds are restricted and are to be used to facilitate expeditious payment of approved claims. &nbsp;The funds are replenished by the insurers and reinsurers as claims are paid by our MGUs.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Short-Term Investments</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Investments with original maturities of 91-days to 1 year are considered short-term investments and are carried at cost which approximates fair value.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">39</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Securities Purchased Under Agreements to Resell and Securities Sold Under Agreements to Repurchase</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Securities purchased under agreements to resell (&quot;resale agreements&quot;) and securities sold under agreements to repurchase (&quot;repurchase agreements&quot;) are carried at the amounts at which the securities will be subsequently resold or repurchased as specified in the agreements. &nbsp;The Company maintains control of securities purchased under resale agreements, values the collateral on a daily basis and obtains additional collateral, if necessary, to protect the Company in the event of default by the counterparties.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investment Securities</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(i)</B> Investments in fixed income securities, redeemable preferred stock equity securities and derivatives (options and options on future contracts) are accounted for as follows:</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(a)</B> Securities which are held for trading purposes are carried at estimated fair value (&quot;fair value&quot;). &nbsp;Changes in fair value are credited or charged, as appropriate, to <A NAME="OLE_LINK4"></A>net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(b)</B> Securities not held for trading purposes which may or may not be held to maturity (&quot;available-for-sale securities&quot;) are carried at fair value. Unrealized gains and losses deemed temporary are credited or charged, as appropriate, directly to accumulated other comprehensive income (a component of stockholders' equity). &nbsp;Premiums and discounts on debt securities purchased at other than par value are amortized and accreted, respectively, to interest income in the Consolidated Statements of Operations, using the constant yield method over the period to maturity. &nbsp;Realized gains and losses on sales of available-for-sale securities, and unrealized losses considered to be other than temporary, are credited or charged, as appropriate, to net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(ii)</B> Financial instruments sold, but not yet purchased, represent obligations to replace borrowed securities that have been sold. &nbsp;Such transactions occur in anticipation of declines in the fair value of the securities. The Company's risk is an increase in the fair value of the securities sold in excess of the consideration received, but that risk is mitigated as a result of relationships to certain securities owned. &nbsp;Unrealized gains or losses on open transactions are credited or charged, as appropriate, to net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;While the transaction is open, the Company will also incur an expense for any accrued dividends or interest payable to the lender of the securities. &nbsp;When the transaction is closed, the Company realizes a gain or loss in an amount equal to the difference between the price at which the securities were sold and the cost of replacing
 the borrowed securities. &nbsp;There were no such transactions outstanding at December 31, 2008 and 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(iii)</B> Realized gains or losses on sales of securities are determined on the basis of specific identification.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(iv)</B> The Company enters into derivative transactions, such as put and call option contracts and options on interest rate futures contracts, to minimize losses on portions of the Company's fixed income portfolio in a rapidly changing interest rate environment. &nbsp;Equity index options are entered into to offset price fluctuations in the equity markets. These derivative financial instruments are all readily marketable and are carried on the Consolidated Balance Sheets at their current fair value with changes in fair value (unrealized gains or losses), credited or charged, as appropriate, to net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. All realized gains and losses are reflected currently in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;Gains (losses) on these instruments were $1,196,000 and $(480,000) during 2008 and 2007, respectively. &nbsp;There were no such derivative transactions outstanding
 at December 31, 2008 and 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(v) </B>Fair value is determined by quoted market prices, where available, or by independent pricing services.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(vi) </B>The Company reviews its investment securities regularly and determines whether other than temporary impairments have occurred. If a decline in fair value is judged by management to </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">40</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>be other than temporary, a loss is recognized by a charge to the Consolidated Statements of Operations, establishing a new cost basis for the security. Beginning with fourth quarter of 2008, for purposes of other-than-temporary impairment evaluation, preferred stocks are treated in a manner similar to debt securities. &nbsp;The factors considered by management in its regular review include, but are not limited to: &nbsp;the length of time and extent to which the fair value has been less than cost; the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer; adverse changes in ratings announced by one or more rating agencies; subordinated credit support; whether the issuer of a debt security has remained current on principal and interest payments; current expected cash flows; whether the decline in fair value appears to be issuer specific or, alternatively, a reflection of general market or indust
ry conditions (including, in the case of fixed maturities, the effect of changes in market interest rates); and the Company's intent and ability to hold the security for a period of time sufficient to allow for a recovery in fair value. &nbsp;For structured securities such as mortgage backed securities, an impairment loss is recognized when there has been a decrease in expected cash flows combined with a decline in the security's fair value below cost.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Fixed Assets</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Fixed assets are stated at cost net of accumulated depreciation. &nbsp;Improvements are capitalized, while repair and maintenance costs are charged to operations as incurred. &nbsp;Depreciation of property and equipment has been provided on the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the respective assets (3 years for computer equipment and 7 years for furniture and fixtures). &nbsp;Amortization of leasehold improvements has been provided on the straight-line method over the shorter of the lease term or the estimated useful life of the asset.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Premium, MGU Fee, and Agency Income Revenue Recognition</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Direct and assumed premiums from short-duration contracts are recognized as revenue over the period of the contracts in proportion to the amount of insurance protection provided. &nbsp;The Company records MGU fee income as policy premium payments are earned. &nbsp;Our MGUs are compensated in two ways. &nbsp;They earn fee income based on the volume of business produced, and collect profit-sharing commissions if such business exceeds certain profitability benchmarks. Profit-sharing commissions are accounted for beginning in the period in which the Company believes they are reasonably estimable, which is typically at the point that claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. Profit-sharing commissions are a function of an MGU attaining certain profitability thresholds and could greatly vary from quarter to qu
arter. &nbsp;Agency income consists of commissions, fees and lead revenue earned by our Agencies.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>MGU and agency income consisted of the following:</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">41</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B><I>Insurance Reserves </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, where material, including legal and other fees and a portion of the Company's general expenses, for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. &nbsp;These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are maintained at levels that are in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;Many factors could affect these reserves, including economic and social conditions, frequency and severity of claims, medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, and changes in doctrines of legal liability and damage awards in litigation. &nbsp;Therefore, the Company's reserves are necessarily based on estimates, assumptions and analysis of historical experience. &nbsp;The Company's results d
epend upon the variation between actual claims experience and the assumptions used in determining reserves and pricing products. Reserve assumptions and estimates require significant judgment and, therefore, are inherently uncertain. &nbsp;The Company cannot determine with precision the ultimate amounts that will be paid for actual claims or the timing of those payments. &nbsp;The Company's estimate of loss represents management's best estimate of the Company's liability at the balance sheet date.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company&#146;s contracts are short-duration and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period&#146;s claims, including losses incurred for claims that have not been reported (&#147;IBNR&#148;). Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:44px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Medical Stop-Loss</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:44px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Liabilities for insurance reserves on certain short-term medical coverages, such as medical stop-loss, are computed using completion factors and expected Net Loss Ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data. &nbsp;Reserves for medical stop-loss insurance are more volatile in nature than those for fully insured medical insurance. &nbsp;This is primarily due to the excess nature of medical stop-loss, with very high deductibles applying to specific claims on any individual claimant and in the aggregate for a given group. &nbsp;The level of these deductibles makes it more difficult to predict the amount and payment pattern of such claims. &nbsp;Furthermore, these excess claims are highly sensitive to changes in factors such as medical trend, provider contracts and medical treatment protocols, adding to the difficulty in predicting claim values and estimating reserves. &nbsp;Also, because medical stop-loss is in excess of an
 underlying benefit plan, there is an additional layer of claim reporting and processing that can affect claim payment patterns. &nbsp;Finally, changes in the distribution of business by effective month can affect reserve estimates due to the timing of claim occurrences and the time required to accumulate claims against the stop-loss deductible.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The two &#147;primary&#148; or &#147;key&#148; assumptions underlying the calculation of loss reserves for medical stop-loss business are (i) projected net loss ratio, and (ii) claim development patterns. &nbsp;The projected net loss ratio is set at expected levels consistent with the underlying assumptions (&#147;Projected Net Loss Ratio&#148;). Claim development patterns are set quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history (&#147;Claim Development Patterns&#148;). &nbsp;The Company uses the Projected Net Loss Ratio to establish reserves until developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results and it is feasible to set reserves based on Claim Development Patterns. &nbsp;The Company has concluded that a reasonably likely change in the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption could have a material effect on the Company&#146;s financial condition, results of operations, or liquid
ity (&#147;Material Effect&#148;) but a reasonably likely change in the Claim Development Pattern would not have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">42</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><I>Projected Net Loss Ratio</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Generally, during the first twelve months of an underwriting year, reserves for medical stop-loss are first set at the Projected Net Loss Ratio, which is set using assumptions developed using completed prior experience trended forward. The Projected Net Loss Ratio is the Company&#146;s best estimate of future performance until such time as developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Major factors that affect the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption in reserving for medical stop-loss relate to: (i) frequency and severity of claims; (ii) changes in medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, the impact of new medical technology and changes in medical treatment protocols; and (iii) the adherence by the MGUs that produce and administer this business to the Company&#146;s underwriting guidelines.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Claim Development Patterns</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Subsequent to the first twelve months of an underwriting year, the Company&#146;s developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate losses. &nbsp;At this point, claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. &nbsp;Development factors based on historical patterns are applied to paid and reported claims to estimate fully developed claims. &nbsp;Claim Development Patterns are reviewed quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history. &nbsp;The Company must determine whether changes in development represent true indications of emerging experience or are simply due to random claim fluctuations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company also establishes its best estimates of claim development factors to be applied to more developed treaty year experience. &nbsp;While these factors are based on historical Claim Development Patterns, actual claim development may vary from these estimates.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Predicting ultimate claims and estimating reserves in Medical Stop-Loss is more complex than first dollar medical and disability business due to the &#147;excess of loss&#148; nature of these products with very high deductibles applying to specific claims on any individual claimant and in the aggregate for a given group. &nbsp;The level of these deductibles makes it more difficult to predict the amount and payment pattern of such claims. &nbsp;Fluctuations in results for specific coverage are primarily due to the severity and frequency of individual claims, whereas fluctuations in aggregate coverage are largely attributable to frequency of underlying claims rather than severity. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Due to the short-term nature of Medical Stop-Loss, redundancies or deficiencies will typically emerge during the course of the following year rather than over a number of years. &nbsp;For Employer Stop-Loss, as noted above, the Company typically maintains its reserves based on underlying assumptions until it determines that an adjustment is appropriate based on emerging experience from all of its MGUs for prior underwriting years. &nbsp;Reserves for HMO Reinsurance are adjusted on a policy by policy basis. &nbsp;Because of the small number of HMO Reinsurance policies it writes or reinsures, the Company is able to evaluate each policy individually for potential liability by reviewing open claims with each HMO and applying completion factors using historical data.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:44px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Fully Insured Health</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Liabilities for insurance reserves for fully insured medical business are established to provide for the liability for incurred but not paid claims. &nbsp;Reserves are calculated using standard actuarial methods and practices. &nbsp;Historical paid claim patterns are reviewed and estimated development factors are applied to immature incurred months to calculate these reserves. &nbsp;The primary assumption in the determination of fully insured reserves is that historical claim </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">43</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>development patterns are representative of future claim development patterns. &nbsp;Factors which may affect this assumption include changes in claim payment processing times and procedures, changes in time delay in submission of claims and the incidence of unusually large claims. &nbsp;Liabilities for fully insured medical reserves and disability coverages are computed using completion factors and expected Net Loss Ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data. &nbsp;The reserving analysis includes a review of claim processing statistical measures and large claim early notifications; the potential impacts of any changes in these factors are not material. &nbsp;The delay in submission of claims tends to be stable over time and not subject to significant volatility.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While these calculations are based on standard methodologies, they are estimates based on historical patterns.&nbsp; To the extent that actual claim payment patterns differ from historical patterns, such estimated reserves may be redundant or inadequate. &nbsp;The effects of such deviations are evaluated by considering claim backlog statistics and reviewing the reasonableness of projected claim ratios.&nbsp; Other factors which may affect the accuracy of reserve estimates include the proportion of large claims which may take longer to adjudicate, changes in billing patterns by providers and changes in claim management practices such as hospital bill audits.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Liabilities for insurance reserves on STM and disability coverages are computed using claim development patterns and projected loss ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management believes that the Company's methods of estimating the liabilities for insurance reserves provided appropriate levels of reserves at December 31, 2008 and December 31, 2007. Changes in the Company's reserve estimates are recorded through a charge or credit to its earnings in the period in which they arise.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Reinsurance</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Amounts recoverable or paid for under reinsurance contracts are included in total assets or total liabilities as due from reinsurers or due to reinsurers. &nbsp;In 2008, Independence American derived most of its business from pro rata quota share reinsurance treaties with Standard Security Life and Madison National Life, which are wholly owned subsidiaries of IHC.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Taxes</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company accounts for income taxes under the asset and liability method<I>.</I> Deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the future tax consequences attributable to differences between the financial carrying amounts of existing assets and liabilities and their respective tax basis, and operating loss and tax credit carry forwards. &nbsp;Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the years in which those temporary differences are expected to be recovered or settled. &nbsp;The effect on deferred tax assets and liabilities of a change in tax rates is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date. Valuation allowances are established when necessary to reduce deferred tax assets where it is more likely than not that the deferred tax asset will not be realized (see Note 13 of Notes to Consolidated Financial S
tatements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In June 2006, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (the &#147;FASB&#148;) issued Interpretation No. 48, Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes &#150; An Interpretation of FASB Statement No. 109 (&quot;Interpretation 48&quot;), which prescribes a recognition threshold and measurement attribute for the financial statement recognition and measurement of a tax position taken or expected to be taken in a tax return. Interpretation 48 also provides guidance on derecognition, classification, interest and penalties, accounting in interim periods, disclosure and transition. &nbsp;Interpretation 48 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2006. &nbsp;The </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">44</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>adoption of Interpretation 48 on January 31, 2007 did not have a material effect on the Company&#146;s financial statements and the Company believes there are no significant tax positions that would require disclosure under Interpretation 48. &nbsp;Interest income or expense and penalties when applicable will be credited or charged, as appropriate, to selling, general and administrative expenses in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;The IRS has completed their audit of the Company&#146;s 2003 and 2004 consolidated income tax returns in the third quarter of 2008 and made no changes to the reported tax for those periods. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Per Common Share</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Basic income per common share is computed using the weighted average number of common stock shares outstanding during the period. &nbsp;Diluted income per common share is computed using the weighted average number of common stock shares and common stock equivalent shares outstanding during the period. &nbsp;Common stock equivalents consist of stock options (using the &quot;treasury stock&quot; method). &nbsp;Common stock equivalent shares are excluded from the computation if the effect is anti-dilutive. &nbsp;As a result of the anti-dilutive effect, common stock equivalent shares have been excluded from the computation of diluted earnings per share for periods presented with a net loss. &nbsp;Included in the diluted earnings per share calculations are 51,000 shares for the year ended December 31, 2007, from the assumed exercise of options using the treasury stock method. &nbsp;For the year ended December 31, 
2008, such shares were deemed anti-dilutive. &nbsp;Net income does not change as a result of the assumed dilution.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Recent Accounting Pronouncements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Recently Issued Accounting Standards</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In November 2008, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&quot;FASB&quot;) issued Emerging Issues Task Force (&#147;EITF&#148;) Issue No. 08-7, <I>&quot;Accounting for Defensive Intangible Assets,&quot;</I> (&quot;EITF No. 08-7&quot;). &nbsp;EITF No. 08-7 applies to defensive intangible assets, which are acquired intangible assets that the acquirer does not intend to actively use but intends to hold to prevent its competitors from obtaining access to them. &nbsp;As these assets are separately identifiable, EITF No. 08-7 requires an acquiring entity to account for defensive intangible assets as a separate unit of accounting. &nbsp;Defensive intangible assets should not be included as part of the cost of the acquirer's existing intangible assets because the defensive intangible assets are separately identifiable. &nbsp;Defensive intangible assets must be recognized at fair value in accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting 
Standards (&quot;SFAS&quot;) 141(R) and SFAS 157. &nbsp;EITF No. 08-7 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2008. &nbsp;The adoption of EITF No. 08-7 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In November 2008, the FASB issued EITF Issue No. 08-6, <I>&quot;Equity Method Investment Accounting&#148;</I> (&#147;EITF No. 08-6&#148;). &nbsp;EITF No. 08-6 requires that the cost basis of an equity method investment be determined by using a cost-accumulation model, which would continue the practice of including transaction costs in the cost of the investment and would exclude the value of contingent consideration. &nbsp;Equity method investments will be subject to other-than-temporary impairment analysis, however, an equity investor shall not separately test and investee&#146;s underlying indefinite-lived intangible assets for impairment. &nbsp;EITF No. 08-6 also requires an equity investor to account for a share issuance by an investee as if the investor had sold a proportionate share if its investment. &nbsp;Any gain or loss to the investor resulting from an investee&#146;s share issuance shall be recognized in earnings. &nbsp;
EITF No. 08-6 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2008. &nbsp;The adoption of EITF No. 08-6 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In June 2008, the FASB issued FSP EITF No. 03-6-1, <I>&#147;Determining Whether Instruments Granted in Share-Based Payment Transactions Are Participating Securities&#148;</I> (&#147;FSP EITF No. 03-6-</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">45</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>1&#148;). &nbsp;FSP EITF No. 03-6-1 addresses whether instruments granted in share-based payment transactions are participating securities prior to vesting and therefore need to be included in the earnings allocation in calculating earnings per share under the two-class method described in SFAS No. 128, <I>&#147;Earnings per Share&#148;. </I>&nbsp;FSP EITF No. 03-6-1 requires companies to treat unvested share-based payment awards that have non-forfeitable rights to dividend or dividend equivalents as a separate class of securities in calculating earnings per share. &nbsp;FSP EITF No. 03-6-1 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2008; earlier application is not permitted. &nbsp;The adoption of FSP EITF No. 03-6-1 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In May 2008, the FASB issued SFAS No. 163, &quot;<I>Accounting for Financial Guarantee Insurance Contracts - An interpretation of FASB Statement No. 60</I>&quot; (&#147;SFAS 163&#148;). &nbsp;SFAS 163 requires that an insurance enterprise recognize a claim liability prior to an event of default when there is evidence that credit deterioration has occurred in an insured financial obligation. &nbsp;It also clarifies how Statement 60 applies to financial guarantee insurance contracts, including the recognition and measurement to be used to account for premium revenue and claim liabilities, and requires expanded disclosures about financial guarantee insurance contracts. &nbsp;It is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2008, except for some disclosures about the insurance enterprise's risk-management activities. SFAS 163 requires that disclosures about the risk-management activities of the i
nsurance enterprise be effective for the first period beginning after issuance. &nbsp;Except for those disclosures, earlier application is not permitted. &nbsp;The adoption of SFAS 163 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In April 2008, the FASB issued FASB Staff Position (&#147;FSP&#148;) FAS 142-3, &#147;<I>Determination of the Useful Life of Intangible Assets.</I>&#148; (&#147;FSP <A NAME="OLE_LINK15"></A><A NAME="OLE_LINK20"></A>FAS 142-3&#148;). &nbsp;FSP FAS 142-3 amends the factors that should be considered in developing renewal or extension assumptions used to determine the useful life of a recognized intangible asset under SFAS No. 142, &#147;<I>Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets</I>.&#148; &nbsp;FSP FAS 142-3 applies prospectively to intangible assets that are acquired, individually or with a group of other assets, after the effective date in either a business combination or asset acquisition. &nbsp;FSP FAS 142-3 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2008, and interim periods within those fiscal years. &nbsp;Early adoption is prohibited. &nbsp;The adoption of FSP FAS 142-3 is not expected t
o have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In March 2008, the FASB issued SFAS No. 161, <I>&#147;Disclosures about Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities&#151;an amendment of FASB Statement No. 133&#148;</I> (&#147;SFAS 161&#148;). &nbsp;SFAS 161 expands the current disclosure requirements for derivative instruments and hedging activities. &nbsp;Entities are required to provide enhanced disclosures about (a) how and why an entity uses derivative instruments, (b) how derivative instruments and related hedged items are accounted for under FASB Statement 133 and its related interpretations, and (c) how derivative instruments and related hedged items affect an entity&#146;s financial position, financial performance, and cash flows. &nbsp;In addition, SFAS 161 requires disclosure of fair values of derivative instruments and their gains and losses in a tabular format as well as cross-referencing within the footnotes to allow users of financial statements to locate important inf
ormation about derivative instruments. &nbsp;SFAS 161 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years and interim periods beginning after November 15, 2008, with early application encouraged. &nbsp;SFAS 161 encourages, but does not require, comparative disclosures for earlier periods at initial adoption. &nbsp;The adoption of SFAS 161 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In February 2008, the FASB issued FSP FAS 140-3, &#147;<I>Accounting for Transfers of Financial Assets and Repurchase Financing Transactions</I>&#148; (&#147;FSP FAS 140-3&#148;). &nbsp;The objective of FSP FAS 140-3 is to provide guidance on accounting for a transfer of a financial asset and a repurchase financing. &nbsp;FSP FAS 140-3 presumes that an initial transfer of a financial asset and a repurchase </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">46</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>financing are considered part of the same arrangement (linked transaction) under Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 140, &#147;<I>Accounting for Transfers and Servicing of Financial Assets and Extinguishments of Liabilities</I>&#148; (&quot;SFAS 140&quot;). &nbsp;However, if certain criteria are met, the initial transfer and repurchase financing shall not be evaluated as a linked transaction and shall be evaluated separately under SFAS No. 140. &nbsp;FSP FAS 140-3 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after November 15, 2008, and interim periods within these fiscal years. &nbsp;Earlier application is not permitted. &nbsp;The adoption of FSP FAS 140-3 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In November 2007, the FASB issued SFAS No. 141 (revised 2007), &#147;<I>Business Combinations</I>&#148; (&#147;SFAS 141(R)&#148;) and SFAS No. 160, &#147;<I>Non-controlling Interests in Consolidated Financial Statements</I>&#148;, an amendment of ARB No. 51 (&#147;SFAS 160&#148;). &nbsp;These standards aim to improve, simplify, and converge internationally the accounting for business combinations and the reporting of non-controlling interests in consolidated financial statements. &nbsp;SFAS 141(R) will change how business acquisitions are accounted for and will impact financial statements both on the acquisition date and in subsequent periods. &nbsp;SFAS 160 will change the accounting and reporting for minority interests, which will be re-characterized as non-controlling interests and classified as a component of equity. &nbsp;SFAS 141(R) and SFAS 160 are effective for both public and private companies for fiscal years beginning on or a
fter December 15, 2008. &nbsp;SFAS 141(R) will be applied prospectively. &nbsp;SFAS 160 requires retroactive adoption of the presentation and disclosure requirements for existing minority interests. &nbsp;All other requirements of SFAS 160 will be applied prospectively. &nbsp;Early adoption is prohibited for both standards. &nbsp;The adoption of SFAS 141(R) and SFAS 160 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Recently Adopted Accounting Standards</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In January 2009, the FASB issued FSP No. EITF 99-20-1, <I>&quot;Amendments to the Impairment Guidance of EITF Issue No. 99-20&quot;</I> (&quot;FSP EITF 99-20-1&quot;). &nbsp;FSP EITF 99-20-1 aligns the impairment guidance in EITF Issue No. 99-20, <I>&quot;Recognition of Interest Income and Impairment on Purchased Beneficial Interests and Beneficial Interests That Continue to be Held by a Transferor in Securitized Financial Assets&quot;</I>, with that in SFAS No. 115, <I>&quot;Accounting for Certain Investments in Debt and Equity Securities&quot;</I>, and other related guidance. &nbsp;The adoption of FSP EITF 99-20-1 did not have a material effect on the Company's consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In December 2008, the FASB issued FSP FAS 140-4 and FIN 46(R)-8, <I>&#147;Disclosures by Public Entities (Enterprises) about Transfers of Financial Assets and Interests in Variable Interest Entities&#148; </I>(&#147;FSP FAS 140-4 and FIN 46(R)-8&#148;). &nbsp;This FSP amends SFAS No. 140, <I>&#147;Accounting for Transfers and Servicing of Financial Assets and Extinguishments of Liabilities&#148;</I>, requiring public entities to provide additional disclosures about transfers of financial assets. &nbsp;It also amends FASB Interpretation No. 46 (revised December 2003), <I>&#147;Consolidation of Variable Interest Entities&#148;</I>, requiring public enterprises, including sponsors that have a variable interest in a variable interest entity, to provide additional disclosures about their involvement with variable interest entities. &nbsp;FSP FAS 140-4 and FIN 46(R)-8 shall be effective for annual or interim periods ending after December 
15, 2008. &nbsp;The adoption of FSP FAS 140-4 and FIN 46(R)-8 did not have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In September 2008, the FASB issued FSP FAS 133-1 and FIN 45-4, <I>&quot;Disclosures about Credit Derivatives and Certain Guarantees: An Amendment of FASB Statement No. 133 and Interpretation No. 45; and Clarification of the Effective Date of FASB Statement No. 161&quot;</I> (&quot;FSP FAS 133-1 and FIN 45-4&quot;). FSP FAS 133-1 and FIN 45-4 expands the disclosure requirements of SFAS 133 for sellers of credit derivatives and hybrid instruments that have embedded credit derivatives to include (a) the nature of the credit derivative, including the approximate term, the reasons for entering into the credit derivative and the events or circumstances that would require </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">47</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>the seller to perform under the credit derivative and the current status of the payment/performance risk of the credit derivative, (b) the maximum potential amount of future payments (undiscounted) the seller could be required to make under the credit derivative, (c) the fair value of the credit derivative, and (d) the nature of (1) any recourse provisions that would enable the seller to recover from third parties any of the amounts paid under the credit derivative, and (2) any assets held either as collateral or by third parties that, upon the occurrence of any specified triggering event or condition, the seller can obtain and liquidate to recover all or a portion of the amounts paid under the credit derivative. With respect to hybrid instruments that have an embedded credit derivative, the seller shall disclose the required information for the entire hybrid instrument, not just the embedded deriv
ative. Disclosure requirements of Interpretation 45 were expanded to include the current status of the payment/performance risk of the guarantee. FSP FAS 133-1 and FIN 45-4 shall be effective for annual or interim periods ending after November 15, 2008. FSP FAS 133-1 and FIN 45-4 encourages, but does not require, comparative disclosures for earlier periods at initial adoption. The adoption of FSP FAS 133-1 and FIN 45-4 did not have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In May 2008, the FASB issued SFAS No. 162, &quot;<I>The Hierarchy of Generally Accepted Accounting Principles</I>&quot; (&#147;SFAS 162&#148;). SFAS 162 identifies the sources of accounting principles and the framework for selecting the principles to be used in the preparation of financial statements of nongovernmental entities that are presented in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States. &nbsp;It is effective 60 days following the Securities and Exchange Commission&#146;s approval of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board amendments to AU Section 411, &quot;<I>The Meaning of Present Fairly in Conformity With Generally Accepted Accounting Principles</I>&quot;, which occurred on September 16, 2008. &nbsp;The adoption of SFAS 162 did not have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In September 2006, the FASB issued SFAS No. 157, which defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring fair value and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. &nbsp;This Statement applies under other accounting pronouncements that require or permit fair value measurements. &nbsp;FASB Staff Position FIN 157-2, &quot;<I>Effective Date of FASB Statement No. 157</I>&quot;, amends SFAS 157 to defer its effective date to fiscal years beginning after November 15, 2008, and for interim periods within those fiscal years. &nbsp;The delayed effective date applies to all non-financial assets and non-financial liabilities except for items that are recognized or disclosed at fair value in the financial statements on a recurring basis (at least annually). &nbsp;FSP FAS 157-3, <I>&quot;Determining the Fair Value of a Financial Asset When the Market for That Asset Is Not Active&quot;</I> clarifies the application of SFAS 157 in a mar
ket that is not active and provides an example to illustrate key considerations in determining the fair value of a financial asset when the market for that financial asset is not active. &nbsp;Revisions resulting from a change in the valuation technique or its application shall be accounted for as a change in accounting estimate. &nbsp;The partial adoption of SFAS 157 for financial assets and liabilities did not have a material impact on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>3. &nbsp;Goodwill</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On April 1, 2008, the Company purchased the remaining 20% interest in Marlton for $3,700,000, which was funded from corporate liquidity, thereby increasing its interest in this medical stop-loss MGU to 100%. &nbsp;The Company reduced minority interest by $39,000 for the 20% interest in net assets acquired. &nbsp;The Company recorded goodwill based on the fair value of the remaining 20% interest at the acquisition date. &nbsp;As a result of the acquisition, the Company also reduced the valuation allowance on deferred tax assets by $436,000 with a corresponding decrease in goodwill for the amount of net operating losses it estimates it will utilize.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On April 15, 2008, the Company acquired certain of the assets and assumed certain of the liabilities of Insurance Producers Group of America, Inc. and its subsidiaries for $1,750,000, which was funded from corporate liquidity. &nbsp;These assets were acquired by IPA, an indirect, 51% owned subsidiary of the Company. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As required by SFAS 142, the goodwill impairment test must be performed annually. &nbsp;Additionally, SFAS 142 states that goodwill shall be tested for impairment between annual tests if an event or circumstances change that would more likely than not reduce the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying amount. &nbsp;<A NAME="OLE_LINK30"></A><A NAME="OLE_LINK31"></A>The Company utilized a discounted cash flow model, which includes residual value, to determine the fair value of the reporting unit. &nbsp;The Company performed its annual test at September 30, 2008 and determined that goodwill was not impaired. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="line-height:normal; margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2008, the Company&#146;s market capitalization was less than its book value indicating a potential impairment of goodwill. &nbsp;As a result, the Company assessed the factors contributing to the performance of AMIC stock in 2008, and concluded that the market capitalization does not represent the fair value of the Company. &nbsp;The Company noted several factors that have led to a difference between the market capitalization and the fair value of the Company, including (i) the Company&#146;s stock is thinly traded and a sale of even a small number of shares can have a large percentage impact on the price of the stock, (ii) IHC and insiders own over 50% of the outstanding shares, which has had a significant adverse impact on the number of shares available for sale and therefore the trading potential of AMIC stock, (iii) the general lack of confidence in equity securities, which has resulted in a fl
ight to US Treasury securities and other investments perceived to be of a higher quality, (iv) both financial institutions and the insurance industry as a whole have seen similar drops in share prices, particularly in the fourth quarter of 2008 as concerns over the effects of the volatile equity and bond markets on insurance company&#146;s investment portfolios are translating into lower share prices. &nbsp;In light of such developments, the Company updated its evaluation at December 31, 2008<FONT style="font-size:11pt"> </FONT>and reaffirmed that goodwill was not impaired. &nbsp;Going forward, the Company changed its annual impairment testing date from September 30 to December 31. &nbsp;If the Company experiences a sustained decline in its results of operations and cash flows, or other indicators of impairment exist, the Company may incur a material non-cash charge to earnings relating to impairment of our goodwill, which could have a material adverse effect on our results. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>

<P style="line-height:normal; margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Intangible asset additions of $1,204,000 in 2008 are a result of the Company&#146;s purchase of the remaining 20% interest in Marlton on April 1, 2008 ($480,000), and the acquisition of certain of the assets and assumption of certain of the liabilities of Insurance Producers Group of America, Inc. and its subsidiaries on April 15, 2008 ($724,000). These assets were acquired by IPA, an indirect, 51% owned subsidiary of the Company. &nbsp;Intangible assets related to the purchase of the remaining 20% interest in Marlton represent broker relationships with an estimated<FONT style="font-size:11pt"> </FONT>useful life of 10 years. &nbsp;Intangible assets related to Insurance Producers Group of America, Inc. and its subsidiaries represent various relationships and proprietary technology with estimated useful life spans of 4 to 12 years.</P>

<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-right:-0.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Government-sponsored enterprise mortgage-backed securities consist of Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation and Federal National Mortgage Association securities.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The amortized cost and fair value of fixed maturities at December 31, 2008 by contractual maturity are shown below. &nbsp;Expected maturities will differ from contractual maturities because borrowers may have the right to call or prepay obligations with or without call or prepayment penalties. &nbsp;The average life of mortgage backed securities is affected by prepayments on the underlying loans and, therefore, is materially shorter than the original stated maturity.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify><BR>

</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">52</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<TABLE style="font-size:10pt" cellspacing=0><TR height=0 style="font-size:0; display:none"><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=0.467></TD><TD width=245.067></TD><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=57></TD><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=76></TD><TD width=16.933></TD><TD width=50></TD><TD width=21.133></TD><TD width=72.8></TD><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=58.067></TD><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=72.267></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Substantially all of the unrealized losses at December 31, 2008 and 2007 relate to investment grade securities and are attributable to changes in market interest rates and general disruptions in the credit market subsequent to purchase. &nbsp;The unrealized losses on corporate securities are due to wider spreads. &nbsp;Spreads have widened as investors shifted funds to US Treasuries in response to the current market turmoil. &nbsp;The Company reviews its investments regularly and monitors its investments for impairments. &nbsp;At December 31, 2008, the Company had $1.9 million invested in whole loan CMOs backed by Alt-A mortgages. &nbsp;Of this amount, 46.3% were in CMOs that originated in 2005 or earlier and 53.7% were in CMOs that originated in 2006. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s mortgage security portfolio has no direct exposure to sub-prime mortgages. &nbsp;The unrealized loss for the equity securities was primarily due to wider spreads 
for preferred stocks issued by financial institutions following the disruption in credit markets in late 2007 and continuing in 2008. &nbsp;Some of these financial institutions have exposure to sub-prime mortgages. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>A total of 30 securities were in a continuous unrealized loss position for less than 12 months and 43 securities for 12 months or longer as of December 2008. &nbsp;A total of 24 securities were in a continuous unrealized loss position for less than 12 months and 51 securities for 12 months or longer as of December 31, 2007. &nbsp;For fixed maturities, there are no securities past due or securities for which the Company currently believes it is not probable that it will collect all amounts due according to the contractual terms of the investment. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Based on management&#146;s review of the portfolio, which considered the various factors described in Note 2 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, the Company recorded a loss of $1,006,000 for other-than-temporary impairments for the twelve months ended December 31, 2008. &nbsp;This was due to the severity of the decrease in fair values and the length of time that these securities were in a loss position. &nbsp;The Company did not record any losses for other-than-temporary impairments for the twelve months ended December 31, 2007. &nbsp;The loss for the twelve months ended December 31, 2008 of $1,006,000 represents a loss on investment grade bonds and preferred stocks of financial institutions that the Company determined to be other-than-temporary. &nbsp;Further deterioration in credit quality of the companies backing the securities, further deterioration in the condition of the financial services industry, a continuation of th
e current imbalances in liquidity that exist in the marketplace, a continuation or worsening of the current economic recession, or additional declines in real estate values may further affect the fair value of these securities and increase the potential that certain unrealized losses be designated as other-than-temporary in future periods and the Company may incur additional write-downs.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company had derivative instruments representing the value of the contingent payment due to EDH as of December 31, 2008 and 2007 (see Note 19 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $50,000 and gross losses of $83,000 were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $112,000 and gross losses of $115,000 were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In the fourth quarter of 2008, the Company became aware of certain activities engaged in by the non-affiliate broker-dealer that managed a trading account of the Company. Net realized investment gains reported in the accompanying Consolidated Statements of Operations for 2008 and 2007 includes income related to the trading account of $142,000 and $324,000, respectively. Short-term investments in the December 31, 2007 consolidated balance sheet include the Company&#146;s investment in the account with a carrying amount of $4,802,000. The carrying amount of the Company&#146;s investment at the time of loss was $2,566,000. &nbsp;The broker-dealer is now in bankruptcy. The Company intends to file a claim and believes it will likely recover the $500,000 </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">53</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>maximum amount available from the Securities Investor Protection Corporation (&#147;SIPC&#148;). Accordingly, the Company recorded a pre-tax loss of $2,006,000, net of expected recoveries, in net realized investment losses in the fourth quarter of 2008 in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;While the Company may be subject to legal claims in this matter, the ultimate resolution of any such claims would not be material to its financial condition.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>6. &nbsp;Fair Value Measurements</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The adoption of SFAS 157 did not have a material impact on our financial statements. &nbsp;SFAS 157 defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring fair value in generally accepted accounting principles and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. &nbsp;SFAS 157 applies whenever other standards require or permit assets or liabilities to be measured at fair value but does not expand the use of fair value in any new circumstances. &nbsp;In this standard, the FASB clarifies the principle that fair value should be based on the assumptions market participants </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">54</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>would use when pricing the asset or liability. &nbsp;In support of this principle, SFAS 157 establishes a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the information used to develop those assumptions.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The valuation techniques required by SFAS 157 are based upon observable and unobservable inputs. &nbsp;Observable inputs reflect market data obtained from independent sources, while unobservable inputs reflect our market expectations. &nbsp;These two types of inputs create the following fair value hierarchy: </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<TABLE style="font-size:10pt" cellspacing=0 align=center><TR height=0 style="font-size:0; display:none"><TD width=73.333></TD><TD width=520.667></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=73.333><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Level 1 &#150;</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=520.667><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Quoted prices for identical instruments in active markets.</P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=73.333><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=520.667><P>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=73.333><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Level 2 &#150;</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=520.667><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Quoted prices for similar instruments in active markets; quoted prices for identical or similar instruments in markets that are not active; and model-derived valuations whose inputs are observable or whose significant value drivers are observable.</P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=73.333><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=520.667><P>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=73.333><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Level 3 &#150;</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=520.667><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Instruments where significant value drivers are unobservable.</P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>When available, we use quoted market prices to determine fair value and classify such items in Level 1. &nbsp;In some cases, we use quoted market prices for similar instruments in active markets and/or model-derived valuations where inputs are observable in active markets and classify such items in Level 2. &nbsp;When there are limited or inactive trading markets, we use industry&#150;standard pricing methodologies, including discounted cash flow models, whose inputs are based on management assumptions and available current market information. &nbsp;These items are classified in Level 3. &nbsp;Further, we retain independent pricing vendors to assist in valuing certain instruments. </P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The following section describes the valuation methodologies we use to measure different financial instruments at fair value. </P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Investments in fixed maturities and equity securities </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Investments included in Level 1 are primarily equities with quoted market prices. &nbsp;Level 2 is primarily comprised of our portfolio of corporate fixed income securities, government agency mortgage-backed securities, government sponsored enterprises (&quot;GSEs&quot;), certain CMO securities, municipals and certain preferred stocks that were priced with observable market inputs. &nbsp;Level 3 securities consist of certain CMO securities, primarily Alt-A mortgages.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Derivative liability </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Financial liabilities consist of a derivative liability relating to the EDH Agreement (see Note 19 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements), and is included in Level 2. &nbsp;The liability is valued using market-observable inputs including market price, interest rate, and volatility within a Black-Scholes model.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:46.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The following table presents our financial assets and liabilities measured at fair value on a recurring basis at December 31, 2008 (in thousands): </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:13pt; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">55</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<TABLE style="font-size:10pt" cellspacing=0><TR height=0 style="font-size:0; display:none"><TD width=220></TD><TD width=22></TD><TD width=64.933></TD><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=22></TD><TD width=64.867></TD><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=22></TD><TD width=72.267></TD><TD width=15.733></TD><TD width=22></TD><TD width=66></TD></TR>

</TD><TD valign=bottom width=15.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=22><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="border-bottom:1px solid #000000" valign=bottom width=64.867><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Level 2</B></P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=15.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=22><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="border-bottom:1px solid #000000" valign=bottom width=72.267><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Level 3</B></P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=15.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=22><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD style="border-bottom:1px solid #000000" valign=bottom width=66><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Total</B></P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=220><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=22><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=64.933><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=22><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=64.867><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=22><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=72.267><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=22><P>&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=66><P>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=220><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>Financial Assets</B></P>
